metadata.title: Cirrus SR22
aws::graph::propositions: Cirrus SR22 Improvements and Variants (2016-2019)
Cirrus introduced improvements to the SR Series in 2016.
Bluetooth wireless connectivity was added to the SR Series in 2016.
Remote keyless entry was added to the SR Series in 2016.
A convenience lighting system was added to the SR Series in 2016.
An easy-access door latch was added to the SR Series in 2016.
Cirrus introduced the SR22 G6 (Generation 6) in 2017.
The SR22 G6 included several major upgrades to the avionics.
The SR22 G6 included new navigation lighting.
Cirrus unveiled the TRAC in September 2019.
The TRAC is a training-oriented version of the SR-series.
The TRAC has a simplified interior.
The TRAC has more durable seat material.
The TRAC has a backseat radio transmit switch.
The backseat radio transmit switch allows an observer to communicate with air traffic control.
The TRAC has integrated engine indication systems.
The TRAC has integrated crew alerting/warning systems.
The TRAC has simulated retractable landing gear controls.
The TRAC has simulated landing gear position lights.
The simulated controls allow cadets and instructors to feign landing gear operation during instructional flights.
The simulated controls allow cadets and instructors to feign landing gear failures during instructional flights.
The actual landing gear on the TRAC remains permanently fixed.

text:
In 2016, Cirrus introduced improvements to the SR Series, including Bluetooth wireless connectivity, remote keyless entry, a convenience lighting system, and an easy-access door latch.
In 2017, the company introduced the SR22 G6 (Generation 6), with several major upgrades to the avionics and new navigation lighting.
In September 2019, Cirrus unveiled the TRAC, a training-oriented version of the SR-series with a simplified interior, more durable seat material, backseat radio transmit switch to allow an observer to communicate with air traffic control, integrated engine indication and crew alerting/warning systems, and simulated retractable landing gear controls and position lights to allow cadets and instructors to feign landing gear operation and failures during instructional flights (the actual landing gear remains permanently fixed).
